												<div class="description author withsidebar">
													<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/manjulamartin/">Manjula Martin</a></h6>
													Manjula Martin is coauthor, with her father, Orin Martin, of <em>Fruit Trees for Every Garden</em>, which won the 2020 American Horticultural Society Book Award, and <em>The Last Fire Season</em>. Her nonfiction has appeared in <em>The New Yorker</em>, <em>Virginia Quarterly Review</em>, <em>The Cut</em>, <em>Pacific Standard</em>, <em>Modern Farmer</em>, and <em>Hazlitt</em>. She edited the anthology <em>Scratch: Writers, Money, and the Art of Making a Living</em>; was managing editor of Francis Ford Coppola’s literary magazine, <em>Zoetrope: All-Story</em>; and has worked in varied editorial capacities in the nonprofit and publishing sectors. She lives in West Sonoma County, California.																									</div>
